{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488893"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"567"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/567"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.06,0.59,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/567"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"567"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94417"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"3732"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"11161"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46089"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of progressive shortness of breath associated with a non-productive cough. She has a medical history of Hodgkin lymphoma and received her third cycle of chemotherapy three weeks ago. She also has atrial fibrillation and hyperthyroidism. Her regular medications include fluconazole, trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole, valacyclovir, metoprolol and carbimazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 105/min and regular, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, oxygen saturation 90% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The jugular venous pressure (JVP) is 2 cm above the sternal angle. On auscultation of the chest, there are vesicular breath sounds, normal vocal fremitus, and widespread inspiratory crackles. There is no pedal oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 110 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ewhite cell count of 5.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelet count 180 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EB-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) 45 pg/mL (\u003C100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anthracycline-induced cardiomyopathy","Community-acquired pneumonia","Bleomycin-induced lung injury","Pulmonary embolism","Cardiac amyloidosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs suggestive of chemotherapy-induced lung injury, most likely due to bleomycin. Bleomycin is a common component of chemotherapy regimens for Hodgkin lymphoma, for example, ABVD (doxorubicin, bleomycin, vinblastine, dacarbazine). It is well-known to cause pulmonary toxicity. The presentation of progressive dyspnoea and non-productive cough, occurring shortly after bleomycin exposure, is typical of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to the risk of pulmonary toxicity, patients require a baseline lung function test, including diffusion capacity for carbon monoxide (DLCO), before receiving bleomycin. The diagnosis of bleomycin-induced lung injury is made by reduced DLCO with compatible pulmonary imaging findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management typically involves cessation of bleomycin and glucocorticoid therapy. It\u0027s important to note that the timing of chemotherapy-induced lung injury can be variable, but it often occurs early in the course of treatment or shortly after subsequent cycles, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleomycin-induced lung injury\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the temporal relationship with chemotherapy, the characteristic presentation of progressive dyspnoea and non-productive cough, and the presence of widespread inspiratory crackles on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnthracycline-induced cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is another potential complication to consider, as it is commonly used in the treatment of Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma as part of the ABVD regimen. However, it typically presents with signs of heart failure, such as peripheral oedema and elevated JVP (\u003E3 cm above sternal angle). The absence of these signs and the normal BNP make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommunity-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E could present similarly, but the absence of fever, normal leucocyte count and vocal fremitus make this less likely than bleomycin-induced lung injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in patients with malignancy, as they are at increased risk of thromboembolism. However, widespread inspiratory crackles are not consistent with pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac amyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition that can cause restrictive cardiomyopathy and subsequent cardiac failure. However, it is not typically associated with Hodgkin lymphoma or its treatment. In this case, the normal JVP and normal BNP also make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bleomycin-induced lung injury is a well-recognised complication of chemotherapy for Hodgkin lymphoma, typically presenting with progressive dyspnoea and non-productive cough.","Patients require a baseline lung function test, including diffusion capacity for carbon monoxide (DLCO) before receiving bleomycin.","The diagnosis of bleomycin-induced lung injury is made by reduced DLCO with compatible pulmonary imaging findings."],"references":["Rosenow EC 3rd, Limper AH. Drug-induced pulmonary disease. Semin Respir Infect 1995; 10:86.","Leger P, Limper AH, Maldonado F. Pulmonary Toxicities from Conventional Chemotherapy. Clin Chest Med 2017; 38:209.","Limper AH. Chemotherapy-induced lung disease. Clin Chest Med 2004; 25:53.","Conte P, Ascierto PA, Patelli G, Danesi R, Vanzulli A, Sandomenico F, et al. Drug-induced interstitial lung disease during cancer therapies: expert opinion on diagnosis and treatment. ESMO Open. 2022 Apr;7(2):100404.","Talley, Nicholas J \u0026 O\u0027Connor, Simon. 2018, Clinical examination / Nicholas Talley, Simon O\u0027Connor. Elsevier Australia (a division of Reed International Books Australia Pty Ltd) Chatswood, NSW"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94417"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"567"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94417"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T20:51:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T20:53:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"567"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"11236